events.summary: Joseph Haydn entered the world in a small Austrian village, where music was more common than groceries, thanks to his father's enthusiasm for folk tunes. His early years were filled with familial harmonies that would make a perfect family sitcom plot!

At the tender age of six, Haydn was shipped off to live with his choirmaster relative, a situation that was surely not the send-off he dreamed of. He managed to survive on breadcrumbs and the occasional lesson while honing his knack for music and avoiding laundry!

After impressing a music director with his singing, Haydn found himself moved to Vienna, where he shared a home with other choir boys and a questionable diet. His primary motivation for singing? A chance at snacks from noble audiences!

Reutter had enough of Haydn's high notes and messy hair, leading to an impromptu eviction. Haydn carried out a classic prank involving scissors, but his mischief turned into freedom as he sought a career on his own terms!

Navigating the freelance world, Haydn played various roles from street serenader to valet-accompanist for a composer who moonlighted as an Italian chef. He eventually found his footing as he honed his craft, raising eyebrows and eyebrows further!
Haydn composed his first opera, 'The Limping Devil', a comedy that had noble audiences laughing—until the censors put an end to the performances. Who knew the devil would offend dignitaries?

After catching the eye of Countess Thun, Haydn's career took flight as he secured aristocratic backing. Teaching music became a lucrative side gig, and soon he was churning out string quartets like a music-making machine!

Haydn landed the prestigious role of Kapellmeister for Count Morzin. With a steady salary and free room and board, he quickly transformed Count Morzin's musical entourage into a budding symphony orchestra, complete with a few fan club members!
Haydn married Maria Anna Theresia Keller, marking the start of a rather unmelodious chapter filled with mutual infidelity and no heirs. Their relationship was more like a sitcom that never aired!

As financial woes forced his previous employer to let him go, Haydn quickly found a gig with the Esterházy family. Royal gigs yielded creative freedom, so he composed more than ever, giving emerging composers a run for their money.

During his time with the Esterházy family, Haydn experimented wildly, leading to music that dazzled listeners and caused a seismic shift in the symphonic tradition. If the classical period had a rockstar, Haydn was headlining!

In a landmark career twist, Haydn renegotiated his contract, allowing him to sell compositions to others. This opened the floodgates to creativity and popularity, making him Europe's hottest composer — all while still stuck in the countryside!

As he worked in the remote palace of Eszterháza, Haydn felt a tinge of loneliness and nostalgia for Vienna. His correspondence with Maria Anna von Genzinger became a sweet escape from palace life — a classic tale of friendship through letters!

Haydn's life came to a close, enveloped by the music he loved so dearly. He left behind a legacy as a pioneering composer who brought joy and innovation to audiences everywhere — and probably some really confused mice in the palace.

Haydn struck up a friendship with fellow composer Mozart, and the two enjoyed making music together in quartets while entertaining friends. Who knew making music could be such a recipe for friendship and fun?

Haydn decided to leave the comforts of Vienna for a lucrative trip to England, where he would conduct new symphonies and bask in the glory of his popularity. Little did he know he was about to make London the place for 'Haydn fever'!

Haydn’s first concert in London caused such a stir that audiences were left electrified, claiming no musical experience had ever thrilled them more. Turns out, he didn't just bring the music — he brought the party!
During his travels in England, Haydn was awarded an honorary doctorate by Oxford University, proving that music was indeed the only degree he needed to be a genius.
By the time he returned to England, Haydn was a celebrated figure, debuting multiple symphonies to wowing audiences. It seemed 'Dr. Haydn' was here to stay and steal the show!
Upon returning to Vienna, Haydn accepted a part-time role as Kapellmeister for the Esterházy family, a gig that came with plenty of workshops and music-writing, but fewer wild night outs!
With both divine inspiration and a significant budget from wealthy benefactors, Haydn composed his famous oratorio, The Creation. Sometimes the muse strikes while balancing a budget!
After years of creating musical magic, Haydn faced declining health, making it difficult to compose. It was a tough pill to swallow when your musical ideas just won't let you rest!
Haydn was honored with a performance of his own work, The Creation, where he arrived in an armchair to crowd applause. It seems even the composer needed a lift now and then for his grand exit!

A grand farewell was thrown in his honor, featuring none other than his own Requiem. It was like the ultimate tribute concert where nobody was there to enjoy it except the spirits floating around and probably some very confused musicians.

With a new contract that let him publish without a nod from his boss, Haydn released his Op. 33 String Quartets, announcing them to the world with all the flair of a magician revealing his latest tricks. It was like he finally got to show off his musical magic without anyone saying, 'Not yet!'

In a revolutionary moment for his career, Haydn managed to elbow his way into the publishing world, getting the green light to sell his own music. It was like he’d discovered a cheat code to a game, and suddenly the world was his oyster—or at least his string quartet!

Haydn packed his bags for England, transforming into a musical ambassador, collecting ideas faster than souvenirs. This trip wasn’t just a vacation; it was like he went to a musical buffet and decided to fill his plate with rhythms and styles that had the locals all jazzed up.

Haydn stumbled upon what he called his 'popular style', which was like adding sprinkles to classical music — it made everything more fun without losing the serious notes. This style featured folk music in clever spots, like putting a surprise confetti pop at the end of a serious speech.

events.event: Return to Vienna and Change in Intentions
events.summary: Upon his return to Vienna, Haydn decided that instead of rushing through compositions for quick cash, he would take his sweet time writing music that would echo through the ages. It's like deciding to cook a gourmet meal instead of reheating leftovers – both satisfying, but one gets you a Michelin star!

With 'The Seasons', Haydn decided to tackle the big questions about life and existence — kind of like attending a deep philosophical seminar but with a much better soundtrack. It took him over a year of stirring thoughts and notes together into something truly sublime.
At the tender age of six, Haydn is taken to Vienna to join the St. Stephen's Cathedral choir, where he learns to hit the high notes—or at least try to without breaking glass.
Haydn lands a position as a music director for Count Morzin. He discovers that composing for a count involves a lot of hobnobbing and less free pizza than he had hoped.
While working for the Esterházy family, Haydn learns that even the grandest of families have drama worthy of the stage—though luckily for him, he was paid to provide the soundtrack.
Haydn visits London and realizes that not only does he have a considerable fan base, but London's tea is terrible compared to home—yet the concerts were worth every scone.
He composes his famous 'Surprise Symphony' to jolt snoozing audiences awake. Spoiler: it worked with a loud bang!
Returning to London earns him even more fame and probably a few more wrinkles, as the city knows how to stress a composer with all those demanding patrons.
Haydn composes his last symphony, marking a grand exit from the stage, leaving behind a legacy that would echo through the ages—or at least until the next composer came along.
